00:12:16,268 --> 00:12:18,964
- What is this?
- Oh, bubble wrap.

219
00:12:19,038 --> 00:12:20,596
<i>(Helen laughs)</i>

220
00:12:20,673 --> 00:12:23,733
The photographer wanted me
to look more buff.

221
00:12:23,809 --> 00:12:27,176
- Ooh.
- You like that?

222
00:12:27,279 --> 00:12:28,906
<i>(pops bubble wrap)</i>

223
00:12:28,981 --> 00:12:31,040
- Hey.
- Mm.

224
00:12:33,085 --> 00:12:34,279
<i>(lots of popping sounds)</i>

225
00:12:34,386 --> 00:12:39,483
<i>(# "Extraordinary" by Liz Phair)</i>

226
00:12:43,496 --> 00:12:46,932
<i># I am extraordinary</i>

227
00:12:46,999 --> 00:12:48,728
- All set, Ms Rosenthal.
- Oh, finally.

228
00:12:48,801 --> 00:12:51,395
Come on in. Thank you for waiting.

229
00:12:51,637 --> 00:12:53,264
Any minute. Any minute.

230
00:12:53,372 --> 00:12:55,101
Christopher, don't make me call for a pizza.

231
00:12:55,174 --> 00:12:56,266
Any minute.

232
00:12:56,342 --> 00:12:57,468
- <i>(Caitlin)</i> Hey.
- <i>(Helen)</i> Hi.

233
00:12:57,543 --> 00:12:59,306
- Hi.
- How are you?

234
00:12:59,378 --> 00:13:01,471
Hi. What is this? Sunday brunch gridlock?

235
00:13:01,547 --> 00:13:05,005
Oh, I know. They just keep on telling us,
"Any minute now," like it's a mantra.

236
00:13:05,251 --> 00:13:07,651
Can we wait like normal, patient adults?

237
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:10,211
- <i>(all)</i> No.
- Christopher. Hi.

238
00:13:13,125 --> 00:13:13,921
<i>(phone rings)</i>

239
00:13:13,993 --> 00:13:16,325
- I would like a Bellini, please.
- Bellini.

240
00:13:16,395 --> 00:13:20,422
- <i>(Caitlin)</i> Ooh, yes. Bellini.
- Bellini. Bellini.

241
00:13:20,499 --> 00:13:23,263
It's my sister.

242
00:13:23,335 --> 00:13:26,133
Jenny, can I call you back?

243
00:13:27,673 --> 00:13:30,301
- Jenny.
- Acceptable guys at 12 o'clock.

244
00:13:30,376 --> 00:13:32,742
Jenny, slow down. I can't hear you.

245
00:13:32,812 --> 00:13:35,940
<i>(male friend)</i>
Are they looking at you or me?

246
00:13:36,015 --> 00:13:37,744
What?

247
00:13:39,785 --> 00:13:41,685
Oh, no.

248
00:13:42,454 --> 00:13:45,218
- Oh, no, Jenny.
- Helen, what's the matter?

249
00:13:45,291 --> 00:13:48,692
- Look at Helen.
- Jenny...

250
00:13:48,794 --> 00:13:52,321
<i>(female friend)</i> Helen, what happened?

251
00:13:53,732 --> 00:13:57,463
Hello. What is it?
Honey, what happened?

252
00:13:57,536 --> 00:13:59,868
<i>(Helen)</i> What?

253
00:13:59,939 --> 00:14:01,873
Are you sure?

254
00:14:07,580 --> 00:14:11,641
Jumped the center divide and he slammed
into them. They didn't have time to react.

255
00:14:11,717 --> 00:14:15,175
- That's what the police think, anyway.
- I'm sorry, Ed.

256
00:14:15,254 --> 00:14:17,950
<i>(woman)</i> I remember when
they bought this house.

257
00:14:18,224 --> 00:14:19,714
So what happens now with the kids?

258
00:14:19,792 --> 00:14:22,727
- Oh, hey.
- Do the kids have any grandparents?

259
00:14:22,795 --> 00:14:28,995
Yes. Paul's parents came from Miami.
They just barely made it today, so...

260
00:14:29,068 --> 00:14:31,161
So sorry.

261
00:14:36,242 --> 00:14:39,370
I'm so, so sorry about your aunt and uncle.

262
00:14:39,445 --> 00:14:41,936
- Thank you.
- Yeah, thank you.

263
00:15:11,944 --> 00:15:15,311
Reverend Hallin spoke so beautifully.

264
00:15:18,117 --> 00:15:20,108
Thanks again, sweetie.

265
00:15:27,393 --> 00:15:30,226
<i>(rattling)</i>

266
00:15:33,532 --> 00:15:35,625
<i>(sniffing)</i>

267
00:15:54,720 --> 00:15:57,245
I'm so sorry.

268
00:15:57,323 --> 00:16:02,818
- So sorry for your loss, Jenny.
- I know, sweetheart. I know.

269
00:16:05,331 --> 00:16:08,300
It smells like Mommy in here.

270
00:16:14,540 --> 00:16:16,701
<i>(Jenny)</i> Guys.

271
00:16:26,585 --> 00:16:28,883
A lot of people are waiting
to pay their respects.

272
00:16:28,954 --> 00:16:33,982
I'm sure they'd appreciate it
if you all came downstairs.

273
00:16:53,746 --> 00:16:56,715
We are gonna get through this.

274
00:16:56,782 --> 00:16:58,875
All right?

275
00:17:01,420 --> 00:17:08,258
Hey, do you mind going to the market for
me and getting some blue party napkins?

276
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:11,955
Now? I mean,
can't we use something else?

277
00:17:12,831 --> 00:17:14,822
Helen.

278
00:17:14,933 --> 00:17:17,265
I've planned the funeral and I've...

279
00:17:17,536 --> 00:17:23,099
I've made the food and taken responsibility
for three very scared children.

280
00:17:23,175 --> 00:17:28,738
All I'm asking you for is four packages
of blue, three-ply dinner napkins

281
00:17:28,814 --> 00:17:34,446
with a seashell design, so that people don't
remember our sister and her husband

282
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:39,150
with paper toweling on their I...
on their laps.

283
00:17:41,860 --> 00:17:44,328
All right.

284
00:17:52,371 --> 00:17:53,395
<i>(doorbell)</i>

285
00:17:53,472 --> 00:17:55,372
- Terribly sorry.
- Thank you.

286
00:17:55,441 --> 00:17:57,170
Hi, I'm Wanda from next door.

287
00:17:57,276 --> 00:17:59,437
If you need anything,
my phone number's on the casserole.

288
00:17:59,511 --> 00:18:01,775
- Thank you.
- And I'm Rudy from across the street.

289
00:18:01,847 --> 00:18:06,250
I also wanted to pay my condolences.
Everyone loved Lindsay and Paul.

290
00:18:07,019 --> 00:18:09,044
<i>(doorbell)</i>

291
00:18:09,121 --> 00:18:11,146
<i>(sighs)</i>

292
00:18:11,223 --> 00:18:13,282
<i>(doorbell)</i>

293
00:18:15,561 --> 00:18:18,428
All right. Come on through
and give your brother a bounce pass.

294
00:18:18,497 --> 00:18:20,556
There you go. Get it up. Yes!

295
00:18:20,632 --> 00:18:23,829
Very good. OK.
Now you give Sarah a bounce pass.

296
00:18:23,902 --> 00:18:26,803
Come on, Sarah.
Come on. Come on, sweetie.

297
00:18:26,872 --> 00:18:28,737
<i>(man)</i> "Section 5."

298
00:18:28,807 --> 00:18:32,265
"Custody and care of the Davis children."

299
00:18:33,712 --> 00:18:37,079
"An account and trust has been set up
at Maplewood Savings Bank,

300
00:18:37,182 --> 00:18:41,141
in the names of Audrey,
Henry and Sarah Davis."

301
00:18:41,253 --> 00:18:45,747
"This bank also holds the mortgage
on the Davis property at 207, Oak Street."

302
00:18:45,824 --> 00:18:50,818
Yes, Larry, and that mortgage is quite
large. We do need to talk about that, also.

303
00:18:50,896 --> 00:18:52,864
We will.

304
00:18:52,931 --> 00:18:56,332
"With regard to custody
of Audrey, Henry and Sarah,

305
00:18:56,568 --> 00:19:00,334
we hereby appoint sole guardianship
of all three children,

306
00:19:00,405 --> 00:19:04,603
imbuing her with all legal rights and
responsibilities that guardianship entails,

307
00:19:04,676 --> 00:19:07,668
to Helen Harris."

308
00:19:09,615 --> 00:19:11,879
What?

309
00:19:11,950 --> 00:19:14,384
- What?
- It's not a mistake.

310
00:19:14,453 --> 00:19:16,819
I prepared this for them myself.

311
00:19:16,889 --> 00:19:20,347
They were very clear. Helen Harris.

312
00:19:27,566 --> 00:19:29,693
Jenny should have them.

313
00:19:29,935 --> 00:19:32,768
I... She's got kids. I...

314
00:19:32,838 --> 00:19:38,606
She's got the mom haircut.
She's Supermom.

315
00:19:39,411 --> 00:19:44,280
She left a letter for each of you
explaining her decision.

316
00:19:46,251 --> 00:19:48,913
You know I handled your mother's will.

317
00:19:48,987 --> 00:19:52,445
Lindsay and Paul's was equally specific.

318
00:19:59,498 --> 00:20:02,365
Good Lord, Lindsay.

319
00:20:02,434 --> 00:20:04,902
Can I read yours?

320
00:20:04,970 --> 00:20:07,165
Helen.

321
00:20:07,239 --> 00:20:09,833
- Are there any contingencies?
- Yes.

322
00:20:09,908 --> 00:20:13,435
If Helen is either unable
or unwilling to care for the children,

323
00:20:13,512 --> 00:20:19,417
- then you, Jenny, are thusly appointed.
- OK, finally, some reason.

324
00:20:19,484 --> 00:20:21,042
Thank you.

325
00:20:21,119 --> 00:20:23,485
God, why didn't you start with that?

326
00:20:23,555 --> 00:20:27,491
Can you imagine Helen raising three kids?

327
00:20:28,694 --> 00:20:30,787
<i>(Helen clears throat)</i>

328
00:20:32,130 --> 00:20:34,894
When should I tell them?

329
00:20:34,967 --> 00:20:37,401
As soon as possible.

330
00:20:40,105 --> 00:20:43,165
- Are you sure?
- Yep.

331
00:20:43,242 --> 00:20:45,608
But we all thought...

332
00:20:45,677 --> 00:20:47,611
Nope.

333
00:20:47,679 --> 00:20:52,446
It's gonna be hard to take care of us
if you're dead too.

334
00:20:53,652 --> 00:20:55,711
This?

335
00:20:56,121 --> 00:20:58,589
Won't kill me for years.

336
00:20:58,657 --> 00:21:02,024
Who's gonna take me to school?

337
00:21:02,094 --> 00:21:03,891
I guess I am.

338
00:21:03,962 --> 00:21:06,453
- And make me chicken fingers?
- Me.

339
00:21:06,531 --> 00:21:09,125
- And give me a bath?
- Me.

340
00:21:09,201 --> 00:21:12,295
And check my nose boogies for infections?

341
00:21:12,971 --> 00:21:16,805
We'll find someone else
to do that last thing.

342
00:21:16,908 --> 00:21:18,967
Come here.

343
00:21:20,078 --> 00:21:22,603
All we gotta do is stick together.

344
00:21:22,681 --> 00:21:25,775
Everything's gonna be OK.

345
00:21:25,884 --> 00:21:30,150
Thanks for trying, Aunt Helen,
but it's not gonna be OK.

346
00:21:31,089 --> 00:21:35,890
Come on, Sarah. It's time for your bath.
Come on, Henry.

347
00:21:36,528 --> 00:21:38,962
Good idea. Great. Uh...

348
00:21:39,031 --> 00:21:44,901
You guys do that, while Aunt Helen
is gonna go out and check the lawn.

349
00:21:46,638 --> 00:21:49,766
Is Aunt Helen older than you, Audrey?

350
00:21:57,015 --> 00:21:59,506
<i>(Audrey whispers)</i> Get farther down.

351
00:21:59,584 --> 00:22:01,984
Is she playing hide-and-go-seek?

352
00:22:02,587 --> 00:22:05,317
<i>(Audrey)</i> I don't think so.

353
00:22:05,390 --> 00:22:07,915
<i>(Henry)</i> We are in deep shit.

354
00:22:09,661 --> 00:22:12,425
<i>(Helen)</i> I love New York pizza.

355
00:22:12,664 --> 00:22:15,462
Aunt Helen, can we go to
the Statue of Liberty tomorrow?

356
00:22:15,567 --> 00:22:18,434
No, because we won't be here...

357
00:22:18,503 --> 00:22:21,995
- Where's Henry?
- He said he'd be right back.

358
00:22:22,107 --> 00:22:24,940
I go to the bathroom for five seconds,
and he's gone?

359
00:22:25,177 --> 00:22:28,510
- With mustard. Here it is.
- I didn't want mustard.

360
00:22:28,613 --> 00:22:29,944
- You don't want mustard?
- No.

361
00:22:30,015 --> 00:22:31,448
All right. No mustard.

362
00:22:31,516 --> 00:22:34,644
- There he is.
- Henry!

363
00:22:34,720 --> 00:22:37,746
- OK? Who's gonna pay for this?
- Aunt Helen.

364
00:22:37,823 --> 00:22:41,884
- You can't do that. You can't just leave.
- I hate pizza. I wanted a hot dog.

365
00:22:41,960 --> 00:22:44,224
- Can you pay Aaron, please?
- I'm Aaron.

366
00:22:44,296 --> 00:22:47,732
Hi, Aaron. I like that he's
making new friends. It's lovely.

367
00:22:47,799 --> 00:22:49,164
<i>(Aaron)</i> Talk me up!

368
00:22:49,234 --> 00:22:52,829
The next time you want something
like a hot dog, you tell me, OK?

369
00:22:52,904 --> 00:22:54,667
- And we'll all go together.
- <i>(Henry)</i> OK.

370
00:22:54,740 --> 00:22:58,608
- Where are we going to dinner?
- This is dinner.

371
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:01,774
<i>(Sarah)</i> Gee, Mommy never
let pizza be our whole dinner.

372
00:23:01,847 --> 00:23:04,873
<i>(Henry)</i> And Dad always said
not to eat and walk at the same time.

373
00:23:04,950 --> 00:23:08,943
<i>(Audrey)</i> Well, they're not here
to yell at us, so it doesn't matter.

374
00:23:09,020 --> 00:23:11,488
<i>(Henry)</i> How many beds do you have
in your apartment, Aunt Helen?

375
00:23:11,556 --> 00:23:14,320
- <i>(Sarah) Aunt Helen!</i>
- <i>(Helen laughs)</i>

376
00:23:15,427 --> 00:23:17,691
- Audrey, your knee.
- Stop!

377
00:23:17,763 --> 00:23:20,630
Hey, guys. Shh!

378
00:23:22,067 --> 00:23:24,627
<i>(lisps)</i> I'm telling you,
if we don't go to sleep right now,

379
00:23:24,703 --> 00:23:29,231
Sleepless Sally gets really upset
when the kids aren't going to sleep.

380
00:23:29,307 --> 00:23:31,605
Where's Sarah? Sarah?

381
00:23:31,676 --> 00:23:34,144
I'm right down here.

382
00:23:34,212 --> 00:23:36,612
Henry's feet stink. Phew!

383
00:23:36,681 --> 00:23:39,673
- <i>(Henry)</i> But I'm a man.
- <i>(Audrey)</i> Give Aunt Helen a whiff.

384
00:23:39,751 --> 00:23:42,948
I don't want to smell your feet.

385
00:23:43,021 --> 00:23:45,649
- Ew! I can smell them from here.
- Ew!

386
00:23:45,724 --> 00:23:47,248
Ew!

387
00:23:47,325 --> 00:23:49,088
Henry!

388
00:23:49,161 --> 00:23:52,995
You need to wash your feet
not once a week.

389
00:23:53,064 --> 00:23:54,053
<i>(Henry)</i> Good night, all.

390
00:23:54,166 --> 00:23:58,330
Audrey, get out of the bathroom.

391
00:23:58,403 --> 00:24:00,394
Fire! Fire!

392
00:24:01,740 --> 00:24:02,900
- Aunt Helen?
- Hm?

393
00:24:03,175 --> 00:24:07,373
Why are we going back? This was great.
We should spend more time here.

394
00:24:07,446 --> 00:24:09,710
- More time?
- Yeah.

395
00:24:09,781 --> 00:24:12,045
We can move here.

396
00:24:13,218 --> 00:24:16,210
We can't sleep every night
in a stinky-feet bed.

397
00:24:16,288 --> 00:24:19,121
We'll move to another apartment.
It's a huge city.

398
00:24:19,191 --> 00:24:23,287
You'll be closer to your job and everything.
You love your job.

399
00:24:23,361 --> 00:24:25,522
- What about Henry and Sarah?
- What about them?

400
00:24:25,597 --> 00:24:29,294
They've got school. They have friends.
You guys grew up in that neighborhood.

401
00:24:29,367 --> 00:24:31,801
That's why. It's a sad neighborhood now.

402
00:24:31,870 --> 00:24:34,771
Everywhere we go there,
we think of Mom and Dad.

403
00:24:34,873 --> 00:24:37,933
- The kids treat me differently.
- We will discuss this later.

404
00:24:38,009 --> 00:24:40,443
Please think about it, Aunt Helen.

405
00:24:40,712 --> 00:24:43,476
OK, we got a train to catch. Let's go.

406
00:24:44,149 --> 00:24:49,382
Henry, stop brushing your teeth.
They're gonna fall out.

407
00:24:50,589 --> 00:24:54,889
- I can't get Hippo in the bag.
- Oh, give it to me.

408
00:24:56,595 --> 00:24:58,688
OK.

409
00:24:59,598 --> 00:25:03,227
There. He's in the bag.
Are you happy now?

410
00:25:03,301 --> 00:25:04,859
<i>(Helen)</i> Henry!

411
00:25:04,936 --> 00:25:07,404
Now, the only thing to do
would be to tell Aunt Jenny.

412
00:25:07,506 --> 00:25:10,236
Thinking about it, Audrey.
I will think about it.

413
00:25:10,308 --> 00:25:15,177
- Tell her we voted.
- I'll think about it, Audrey.

414
00:25:15,247 --> 00:25:17,374
I understand the children's feelings,

415
00:25:17,449 --> 00:25:20,714
- but that's not part of the plan.
- That's <i>your</i> plan, Jenny.

416
00:25:20,785 --> 00:25:24,812
All right, well, what about the idea
of not selling Lindsay's house?

417
00:25:24,890 --> 00:25:27,825
I know you guys offered to pay
the mortgage, but it's enormous.

418
00:25:27,893 --> 00:25:31,385
I spoke to the bank,
and the mortgage is too much for us.

419
00:25:31,463 --> 00:25:36,400
All right. Besides being my idea,
what's wrong with moving down the block?

420
00:25:36,468 --> 00:25:40,165
I mean, I think
the calm of the familiar is better

421
00:25:40,238 --> 00:25:43,230
than the overwhelming
hustle-bustle of the city.

422
00:25:43,341 --> 00:25:46,742
Guys, can you please keep the coloring
on the eggs and not each other?

423
00:25:46,811 --> 00:25:48,278
Oh, no, no, no. No.

424
00:25:48,513 --> 00:25:54,816
Jenny, Sarah thinks that Hippo's parents
are on vacation. That they're coming back.

425
00:25:54,886 --> 00:25:58,982
Henry walks around like a zombie
and draws skeletons.

426
00:25:59,057 --> 00:26:01,821
- Audrey is my only ally.
- You really have to watch her.

427
00:26:02,093 --> 00:26:04,926
Look, they're not happy.
And they've told me themselves.

428
00:26:05,096 --> 00:26:07,462
They're not gonna be happy
anywhere right now.

429
00:26:07,532 --> 00:26:11,059
OK, OK. Wait. Wait.
Let us talk for a minute.

430
00:26:11,136 --> 00:26:14,572
Wait till you see what the Easter Bunny
brings. He's gonna bring lots more eggs.

431
00:26:14,639 --> 00:26:18,871
The Easter Bunny's not coming.
The Easter Bunny joined 50 Cent.

432
00:26:18,944 --> 00:26:23,313
- <i>(Audrey)</i> Why are you being a brat?
- <i>(Henry)</i> You're a brat.

433
00:26:23,381 --> 00:26:26,612
Helen is right.
A change might do them some good.

434
00:26:26,685 --> 00:26:29,483
And if it doesn't work out,
they can always move back here to Jersey.

435
00:26:29,554 --> 00:26:31,988
<i>(Audrey)</i> Ew, you got some in my hair.

436
00:26:32,257 --> 00:26:35,693
- <i>(Sarah)</i> You know what? You know what?
- <i>(Helen)</i> Oh!

437
00:26:35,760 --> 00:26:39,821
- Oh, no.
- You're not very good at this, Aunt Helen.

438
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:44,093
- Stop it!
- Irwin's after ya!

439
00:26:44,169 --> 00:26:50,233
- Turtles carry... carry diseases.
- Stop it. Sarah, please.

440
00:26:50,308 --> 00:26:55,007
We have to find an apartment.
We need to help Aunt Helen.

441
00:26:55,246 --> 00:26:57,476
OK? By being quiet.

442
00:26:59,517 --> 00:27:02,247
<i>(smacks lips noisily)</i>

443
00:27:02,520 --> 00:27:05,182
<i>(clicks tongue)</i>

444
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,264
Stop it.

445
00:27:18,837 --> 00:27:20,737
Stop.

446
00:27:26,244 --> 00:27:28,872
<i>(Helen clicks her pen)</i>

447
00:27:39,557 --> 00:27:41,388
<i>(screams)</i>

448
00:27:48,633 --> 00:27:51,033
<i>(Helen)</i> No.

449
00:27:51,102 --> 00:27:52,865
Chelsea. No.

450
00:27:52,937 --> 00:27:57,237
You know, I hear there's
some pretty decent stuff in Queens.

