<i>(Nilma)</i> Baggy-pant little diaper boy,
go home to mama.

910
00:56:25,348 --> 00:56:29,341
I'm serious. You get out of here.

911
00:56:29,419 --> 00:56:31,250
I said go! Get out of here.

912
00:56:31,321 --> 00:56:34,620
Back home with your baggy pants
and your diapers.

913
00:56:34,691 --> 00:56:37,159
Go home, naughty boy.

914
00:56:39,262 --> 00:56:41,093
Good night, Helen.

915
00:56:41,664 --> 00:56:44,633
What is the matter with you?

916
00:56:45,835 --> 00:56:49,828
Don't you remember
what it's like to be young?

917
00:56:51,374 --> 00:56:53,501
Of course I remember.

918
00:56:53,576 --> 00:56:55,976
It was last Wednesday.

919
00:57:05,688 --> 00:57:07,417
Hi.

920
00:57:09,759 --> 00:57:12,353
Can I ask you a question?

921
00:57:14,030 --> 00:57:16,590
What was Lindsay thinking?

922
00:57:25,642 --> 00:57:29,772
So listen, don't worry about it.
They'll appreciate it when they're older.

923
00:57:29,879 --> 00:57:32,143
I know. I just hate being hated.

924
00:57:32,415 --> 00:57:35,043
I love it.

925
00:57:35,118 --> 00:57:38,884
- I don't have that relationship...
- You do.

926
00:57:38,955 --> 00:57:43,915
You know, you can tell me
all your problems, really. I'm a solver.

927
00:57:43,993 --> 00:57:47,394
I once got an axle-grease stain out of silk.

928
00:57:47,464 --> 00:57:51,730
OK, solver, can you find me a job
close to home with decent pay?

929
00:57:51,801 --> 00:57:54,929
And a dental plan for the cavity triplets?

930
00:57:55,004 --> 00:57:57,632
My husband Ravi.

931
00:58:04,848 --> 00:58:06,543
Do you know where I can find
a Ravi Prasad?

932
00:58:06,616 --> 00:58:08,675
Yeah, he's inside.

933
00:58:10,620 --> 00:58:12,679
You'll see, we're like one big family here.

934
00:58:12,755 --> 00:58:16,851
Now, the owner, Mr Massey, nice guy,
very fair, but he's picky about who he hires.

935
00:58:16,926 --> 00:58:19,793
Hey, Ralphy, any takers
on that lime-green baby?

936
00:58:19,863 --> 00:58:20,830
You wise guy.

937
00:58:20,897 --> 00:58:24,333
- I still got five bucks says you'll sell it.
- You're on.

938
00:58:24,534 --> 00:58:28,971
We got... We got stuck with this
lime-green Lincoln. Been here for months.

939
00:58:29,038 --> 00:58:32,235
Mr Massey's offering a ham
to the first person who can sell it.

940
00:58:32,308 --> 00:58:34,037
- A ham?
- Oh, yeah.

941
00:58:34,110 --> 00:58:37,102
Guys are big on free meats round here.

942
00:58:37,180 --> 00:58:39,978
Now, listen. Mr Massey's a little nervous.

943
00:58:40,216 --> 00:58:43,811
He acted in his first
on-camera TV commercial today.

944
00:58:43,887 --> 00:58:46,947
<i>And see me, Mickey Massey,</i>
<i>a name you can trust.</i>

945
00:58:47,023 --> 00:58:49,184
<i>Uh... Yeah, I forgot to point.</i>

946
00:58:49,259 --> 00:58:55,562
<i>You want a deal on a previously owned</i>
<i>car? Well, come... Charlie! Charlie!</i>

947
00:58:55,632 --> 00:58:58,465
<i>It's me. Yeah. Commercial.</i>

948
00:58:58,535 --> 00:58:59,399
<i>(knock at door)</i>

949
00:58:59,502 --> 00:59:01,834
<i>You want a deal on a previously owned</i>
<i>car? Come to Massey Motors...</i>

950
00:59:02,105 --> 00:59:03,800
Come in.

951
00:59:04,674 --> 00:59:05,333
Thank you.

952
00:59:05,408 --> 00:59:06,670
<i>Yeah, I pointed the wrong way again.</i>

953
00:59:07,110 --> 00:59:12,742
- Hi, I'm Helen.
- Sit. I'll be with ya in a second. Just sit.

954
00:59:12,815 --> 00:59:16,114
<i>Remember: Massey means trust.</i>

955
00:59:18,988 --> 00:59:22,116
- What'd you think of that?
- I believe it.

956
00:59:22,191 --> 00:59:26,719
Don't. Massey doesn't mean trust.
It means hillside in French.

957
00:59:26,796 --> 00:59:29,424
I can't do dishonest.

958
00:59:30,500 --> 00:59:33,025
Ravi, we're reshooting that commercial.

959
00:59:33,102 --> 00:59:37,903
Honest. We need an honest commercial,
Ravi. All right?

960
00:59:37,974 --> 00:59:40,875
- I'm sorry. Ms Helen Harris. OK.
- Yes.

961
00:59:40,944 --> 00:59:45,142
- How long did you work as a secretary?
- Actually, I wasn't a secretary.

962
00:59:45,214 --> 00:59:49,014
As it states right there, I was an
executive assistant to Dominique Courier,

963
00:59:49,085 --> 00:59:52,316
and I had a promise of promotion to agent.

964
00:59:52,388 --> 00:59:53,616
OK.

965
00:59:53,690 --> 00:59:59,219
You seem like a nice girl, Helen.
And you're a friend of Ravi and Nilma's.

966
00:59:59,462 --> 01:00:01,555
All right, we're looking for a receptionist.

967
01:00:01,631 --> 01:00:04,361
The pay is 17.50 an hour,
the hours are nine to five.

968
01:00:04,434 --> 01:00:07,198
So, how does that suit you, hm?

969
01:00:07,270 --> 01:00:10,171
I always thought I could have
a career in used cars one day.

970
01:00:10,239 --> 01:00:15,267
We don't sell used cars.
Previously owned or prior-owned cars.

971
01:00:15,345 --> 01:00:16,539
Prior-owned.

972
01:00:16,613 --> 01:00:20,515
Now, you just have to pass
one little test, OK?

973
01:00:26,055 --> 01:00:27,716
<i>(feedback)</i>

974
01:00:27,790 --> 01:00:30,350
Ravi to Parts.

975
01:00:30,693 --> 01:00:32,957
Ravi to Parts.

976
01:00:35,331 --> 01:00:39,199
<i>(louder)</i> Ravi to Parts. Ravi to Parts.

977
01:00:39,802 --> 01:00:42,168
Ralphy to the showroom.

978
01:00:42,338 --> 01:00:45,364
Ralphy to the showroom.

979
01:00:49,846 --> 01:00:51,575
Yeah?

980
01:00:53,316 --> 01:00:56,012
Helen to Payroll.

981
01:01:10,933 --> 01:01:12,924
Hello.

982
01:01:24,414 --> 01:01:29,147
She made the cover!
I know this girl. I know her.

983
01:01:29,218 --> 01:01:33,746
- She looks beautiful.
- So how many copies d'you want?

984
01:01:35,758 --> 01:01:37,487
None.

985
01:01:59,816 --> 01:02:04,981
Good. Get your hands washed, guys.
Hey, you, look, look, look. Hello, hello.

986
01:02:05,054 --> 01:02:10,549
- Hello, sweetie. Happy Mother's Day.
- <i>(Helen)</i> Happy Mother's Day.

987
01:02:10,793 --> 01:02:12,624
- You.
- Aunt Jenny, hey.

988
01:02:12,695 --> 01:02:18,224
Oh, gosh. Everybody, please sit down.
All right. We're going to eat right away.

989
01:02:18,334 --> 01:02:24,068
So, um, did you remember
to bring your letter?

990
01:02:24,140 --> 01:02:27,576
- Oh, of course I did.
- Mm-hm. Oh.

991
01:02:27,643 --> 01:02:33,104
- Not until you show me yours.
- Well, why don't we just do it after dinner?

992
01:02:33,182 --> 01:02:35,446
- <i>(dog barks)</i>
- Stay!

993
01:02:35,518 --> 01:02:37,315
<i>(whines)</i>

994
01:02:37,386 --> 01:02:40,150
What happened with the train?
Was there a delay?

995
01:02:40,223 --> 01:02:43,715
No, no. Audrey was making samosas
at Nilma's, so we caught the next train.

996
01:02:43,793 --> 01:02:45,920
Mm-hm. Just one?

997
01:02:47,063 --> 01:02:51,295
Well, they were hungry
so they ate them on the way.

998
01:02:52,802 --> 01:02:54,292
Can I help you with something, Jenny?

999
01:02:54,370 --> 01:02:57,771
You know what?
I've got everything organized.

1000
01:02:57,840 --> 01:02:59,535
Ooh. Ooh.

1001
01:02:59,609 --> 01:03:03,477
Sweetie, what did Mommy say about
kicking when she's having a conversation?

1002
01:03:03,546 --> 01:03:06,208
You need to wait until she's finished.

1003
01:03:06,282 --> 01:03:08,375
Thank you very much.

1004
01:03:08,451 --> 01:03:11,079
Did you just boss around the unborn?

1005
01:03:12,822 --> 01:03:16,656
It's never too early
to start learning manners.

1006
01:03:16,726 --> 01:03:19,456
OK, kids. We're ready.

1007
01:03:20,963 --> 01:03:23,557
Whoa!

1008
01:03:24,033 --> 01:03:25,694
Wow!

1009
01:03:25,968 --> 01:03:28,368
- Oh, my gosh.
- <i>(Jenny)</i> Look at that. Hey, guys.

1010
01:03:28,437 --> 01:03:30,667
- Holy cow.
- Yeah.

1011
01:03:30,740 --> 01:03:32,571
- Oliver, did you wash your hands?
- Yes, Mom.

1012
01:03:32,642 --> 01:03:36,078
Everything tastes great, honey. You
shouldn't have to cook on Mother's Day.

1013
01:03:36,145 --> 01:03:42,084
You know I don't mind.
Being a mom is the greatest job on earth.

1014
01:03:43,052 --> 01:03:46,351
I know your mom felt that way.

1015
01:03:48,024 --> 01:03:49,958
- Jenny.
- What?

1016
01:03:50,026 --> 01:03:54,861
We all love her. We miss her.
We can mention her. Can't we?

1017
01:03:55,498 --> 01:03:58,023
I don't like to.

1018
01:03:59,535 --> 01:04:01,799
<i>(Sarah)</i> Me neither.

1019
01:04:06,108 --> 01:04:08,838
You know, would you kids like
to talk about what you've been reading?

1020
01:04:08,911 --> 01:04:11,311
- Harry Potter.
- Harry Potter.

1021
01:04:11,380 --> 01:04:14,315
- Stuff by Shank 54.
- Huh.

1022
01:04:14,383 --> 01:04:18,183
- That sounds interesting. Who's that?
- He writes poems.

1023
01:04:18,254 --> 01:04:21,712
On the side of our building.
With spray paint at four in the morning.

1024
01:04:21,791 --> 01:04:23,952
Sometimes I help when I can't sleep

1025
01:04:24,026 --> 01:04:28,656
because Aunt Helen's on a date
or Audrey's on the Internet talking dirty

1026
01:04:28,731 --> 01:04:31,666
or Sarah's crying
because we forgot to feed her again.

1027
01:04:31,734 --> 01:04:33,258
Henry.

1028
01:04:33,336 --> 01:04:35,065
What?

1029
01:04:36,572 --> 01:04:38,972
Jenny, no.

1030
01:04:39,041 --> 01:04:44,206
Henry, what are you talking about?
Is this some kind of joke?

1031
01:04:44,280 --> 01:04:46,646
I don't know why
you keep saying things like this.

1032
01:04:46,716 --> 01:04:48,843
It's not funny.

1033
01:04:48,918 --> 01:04:51,478
- I thought it was funny.
- Thank you.

1034
01:04:51,988 --> 01:04:56,152
Henry was making all of that up, Jenny.
Jenny, what are you doing?

1035
01:04:56,225 --> 01:05:00,321
"When a problem comes along
you must whip it. Before the cream..."

1036
01:05:00,396 --> 01:05:02,921
- Jenny, give me my letter.
- That's it?

1037
01:05:02,999 --> 01:05:05,524
That's all she left behind
to explain why she chose you?

1038
01:05:05,601 --> 01:05:09,264
- The lyrics to "Whip lt"?
- It makes sense to me.

1039
01:05:09,338 --> 01:05:13,900
What is it with you two and that song?
It's ridiculous. I don't get it.

1040
01:05:13,976 --> 01:05:16,570
- Exactly!
- What are you saying?

1041
01:05:16,646 --> 01:05:23,176
That that's the point? I'm no fun? That I
don't get things? That I never make jokes?

1042
01:05:23,286 --> 01:05:25,584
Show me your letter.

1043
01:05:25,855 --> 01:05:27,345
No.

1044
01:05:27,423 --> 01:05:30,654
No? No? What do you mean "no"?

1045
01:05:30,726 --> 01:05:33,490
We said you would read my letter
and I would read yours.

1046
01:05:33,562 --> 01:05:35,792
This is not a letter.

1047
01:05:35,865 --> 01:05:40,598
These are lyrics. Nonsensical lyrics.
This is not a letter.

1048
01:05:40,670 --> 01:05:45,607
If this was a letter, you could read my letter,
but this is not a letter.

1049
01:05:45,675 --> 01:05:48,007
<i>(Helen)</i> Not a letter?

1050
01:05:48,077 --> 01:05:49,510
What?

1051
01:05:49,578 --> 01:05:52,513
You are a smug,

1052
01:05:52,615 --> 01:05:55,778
bitter, colossal bitch.

1053
01:05:56,052 --> 01:05:56,814
<i>(whines)</i>

1054
01:05:56,886 --> 01:05:58,820
OK. Guys.

1055
01:05:58,888 --> 01:06:03,416
I think this is a good time
to take Origami for a walk.

1056
01:06:03,492 --> 01:06:05,426
No, we'll miss the fight.

1057
01:06:05,494 --> 01:06:10,193
If you're finished,
I think I'd like to serve dessert.

1058
01:06:10,266 --> 01:06:14,225
<i>(Helen)</i> You don't wanna help me,
you just wanna judge me.

1059
01:06:14,303 --> 01:06:18,797
Let's all go into the living room and listen
to Jasmine play the piano with one arm.

1060
01:06:19,041 --> 01:06:22,943
You just wanna prove that you're a better
mother than me, that Lindsay was wrong.

1061
01:06:23,179 --> 01:06:27,343
Why would I need to prove that?
Of course I'm a better mother than you.

1062
01:06:27,416 --> 01:06:32,217
I've been doing it forever. But does that
matter? No. She still chose you over me.

1063
01:06:32,288 --> 01:06:38,227
Exactly. <i>She</i> chose, Jenny. Not me.
I had no control over it.

1064
01:06:38,294 --> 01:06:43,561
You're angry with me because
of a decision that <i>she</i> made <i>for</i> me.

1065
01:06:43,632 --> 01:06:47,329
<i>#</i> Merrily, merrily, merrily, merrily
Life is...

1066
01:06:47,403 --> 01:06:52,739
I am giving up everything for these kids,
and you have no idea what that's like.

1067
01:06:52,808 --> 01:06:56,039
I don't know what it's like?
How do you think I got this way?

1068
01:06:56,145 --> 01:07:00,206
Whatever this way is
that's so particularly unfun and funny.

1069
01:07:00,282 --> 01:07:03,547
- Who changed your diapers?
- Don't start with that.

1070
01:07:03,619 --> 01:07:06,019
Mom died when I was seven.

1071
01:07:06,088 --> 01:07:10,889
- Who fed you? Who baby-sat you?
- Lindsay was there, too.

1072
01:07:11,127 --> 01:07:13,288
Lindsay was in New York
trying to be a dancer

1073
01:07:13,362 --> 01:07:15,887
and I was at home
not having a normal childhood

1074
01:07:15,965 --> 01:07:18,195
cos I was too busy being your mommy.

1075
01:07:18,434 --> 01:07:21,870
And you're Tra-La-La Helen.

1076
01:07:22,938 --> 01:07:25,873
So... free.

1077
01:07:26,876 --> 01:07:33,440
Miss Party-Party-All-Night-Long
and I never ever got to feel like that, ever.

1078
01:07:34,683 --> 01:07:37,379
Not once.

1079
01:07:41,991 --> 01:07:44,926
I don't wanna fight any more.

1080
01:07:49,165 --> 01:07:51,759
Happy Mother's Day.

1081
01:07:58,874 --> 01:08:00,569
<i>(referee blows whistle)</i>

1082
01:08:00,643 --> 01:08:03,441
42 - foul.

1083
01:08:03,512 --> 01:08:06,037
- Flagrant.
- <i>(commentator) One minute left.</i>

1084
01:08:06,115 --> 01:08:08,242
Maybe I can come see you DJ sometime.

1085
01:08:08,484 --> 01:08:13,319
I don't know, Miss Audrey. I'm not spinning
no kids' birthday parties, you know?

1086
01:08:13,389 --> 01:08:16,085
- You got a fake ID?
- Course.

1087
01:08:17,560 --> 01:08:20,358
<i>Nurse Wilson says he's OK.</i>

1088
01:08:21,397 --> 01:08:24,560
When's Henry gonna play, Aunt Helen?

1089
01:08:24,633 --> 01:08:26,362
Uh...

1090
01:08:27,536 --> 01:08:30,733
Hey, Coach. This isn't the NBA Finals.

1091
01:08:30,806 --> 01:08:33,934
What happens to "everybody plays"?
Why don't you put Henry in?

1092
01:08:34,009 --> 01:08:36,876
<i>3, 2, 1.</i>

1093
01:08:36,946 --> 01:08:39,813
<i>And Saint Barbara's wins.</i>

1094
01:08:41,450 --> 01:08:43,145
- Excuse me.
- Yes?

1095
01:08:43,219 --> 01:08:46,620
- Hi. Excuse me. What is your problem?
- Aunt Helen, please.

1096
01:08:46,689 --> 01:08:49,214
I know, I...
He could be one of your best players.

1097
01:08:49,291 --> 01:08:53,887
He doesn't wanna play
so you need to square that away with him.

1098
01:08:53,963 --> 01:08:56,955
- You're the coach.
- <i>(Henry)</i> Just forget about it.

1099
01:08:57,032 --> 01:08:59,193
I'm gonna go change.

1100
01:09:01,337 --> 01:09:05,273
I'm sorry that I yelled at you, Dan,
but I've been battling with the kids,

1101
01:09:05,341 --> 01:09:11,177
I'm fighting with my sister and
we're too stubborn to talk to each other.

1102
01:09:11,247 --> 01:09:13,579
I guess I'm just edgy.

1103
01:09:14,350 --> 01:09:18,343
Hey, nobody ever said
it was gonna be easy. Right?

1104
01:09:18,420 --> 01:09:21,048
Yeah, try doing it on your own.

1105
01:09:21,123 --> 01:09:23,250
We got a lot of people around here who do.

1106
01:09:23,325 --> 01:09:27,159
Matt Higgins' mom, she took a pay cut,
she works out of her house.

1107
01:09:27,229 --> 01:09:31,222
And Tommy Meyers' dad is with the kids
all day long, then he works at night.

1108
01:09:31,300 --> 01:09:34,269
I mean, it's tough, but it can be done.

1109
01:09:34,336 --> 01:09:38,932
- Hey, you know what you need?
- A nanny. But I can't afford one.

1110
01:09:39,208 --> 01:09:42,473
You need some fun.
I'm just the man to provide it.

1111
01:09:42,545 --> 01:09:44,706
What are you doing on Sunday?

1112
01:09:44,813 --> 01:09:48,078
- Going to church, of course.
- Yeah, right.

1113
01:09:48,150 --> 01:09:50,277
Nice try.

1114
01:09:50,352 --> 01:09:55,380
- You and the kids. Sunday afternoon.
- What do you have in mind?

1115
01:09:56,592 --> 01:10:01,256
Today we're at the Central Park Zoo,
where every spring a prayer is said,

1116
01:10:01,330 --> 01:10:04,663
blessing the animals
and the newborn babies.

1117
01:10:04,733 --> 01:10:05,859
Pastor.

1118
01:10:05,935 --> 01:10:09,564
Dear Lord, we humbly ask
that you bless these animals

1119
01:10:09,638 --> 01:10:12,300
and all your creatures
throughout the world.

1120
01:10:12,575 --> 01:10:15,669
Blessed are you, Lord. Amen.

1121
01:10:19,381 --> 01:10:21,713
OK, who wants
a private tour of the zoo, huh?

1122
01:10:21,951 --> 01:10:24,715
- <i>(Sarah)</i> Yeah!
- <i>(Henry)</i> Yeah! All right, Pastor Dan.

1123
01:10:24,787 --> 01:10:27,881
<i>(# "At the Zoo" by Simon and Garfunkel)</i>

1124
01:10:29,725 --> 01:10:32,558
<i># I do believe it</i>

1125
01:10:32,628 --> 01:10:35,927
<i># I do believe it's true</i>

1126
01:10:35,998 --> 01:10:38,728
<i># Mm-hm-hm</i>

1127
01:10:38,901 --> 01:10:41,961
<i># Mm-hm-hm</i>

1128
01:10:42,037 --> 01:10:44,403
<i># Whoa-oh</i>

1129
01:10:44,473 --> 01:10:47,237
<i># Mm-hm-hm</i>

1130
01:10:47,309 --> 01:10:50,107
<i># It's a light and tumble journey</i>

1131
01:10:50,179 --> 01:10:52,943
<i># From the east side to the park</i>

1132
01:10:53,015 --> 01:10:58,851
<i># Just a fine and fancy ramble to the zoo</i>

1133
01:10:59,755 --> 01:11:04,715
<i># But you can take a crosstown bus</i>
